📘 AI Coding Agent Playbook: Connecting eBay API Data to Dashboards
🔑 Core Principles

Never expose eBay API keys or tokens to the frontend.
All API calls must go through the backend.

Always handle OAuth2.0 tokens correctly.

Fetch token → Refresh token → Use token in API calls.

Keep code modular.

One service for authentication.

One service for fetching data.

One API layer for frontend consumption.

🏗️ Workflow Overview

Authenticate with eBay (OAuth2.0).

Fetch data from eBay (Orders, Inventory, Messages, etc.).

Expose that data via backend routes (REST/GraphQL).

Frontend fetches from backend → renders into dashboard components.

⚙️ Step 1: Authentication Module

The agent should always build a reusable auth service.

Python Example (auth_service.py):

import base64, httpx, os

APP_ID = os.getenv("EBAY_APP_ID")
CERT_ID = os.getenv("EBAY_CERT_ID")
REDIRECT_URI = os.getenv("EBAY_REDIRECT_URI")

def get_access_token(auth_code: str):
    basic_auth = base64.b64encode(f"{APP_ID}:{CERT_ID}".encode()).decode()
    headers = {
        "Content-Type": "application/x-www-form-urlencoded",
        "Authorization": f"Basic {basic_auth}"
    }
    data = {
        "grant_type": "authorization_code",
        "code": auth_code,
        "redirect_uri": REDIRECT_URI
    }
    response = httpx.post(
        "https://api.ebay.com/identity/v1/oauth2/token", 
        headers=headers, 
        data=data
    )
    return response.json()["access_token"]


✅ Rule for Agent:

Always isolate token logic in a dedicated file/service.

Always read credentials from environment variables.

⚙️ Step 2: eBay Data Fetching

The agent should create modular API clients for each eBay endpoint.

Example: Orders Service (ebay_orders.py):

import httpx

def get_orders(token: str):
    headers = {"Authorization": f"Bearer {token}", "Content-Type": "application/json"}
    url = "https://api.ebay.com/sell/fulfillment/v1/order"
    resp = httpx.get(url, headers=headers)
    return resp.json().get("orders", [])


✅ Rule for Agent:

Always make backend calls with the latest token.

Always return parsed JSON, not raw responses.

⚙️ Step 3: Backend API for Frontend

The agent should expose clean API endpoints for the frontend to consume.

FastAPI Example (main.py):

from fastapi import FastAPI
from ebay_orders import get_orders

app = FastAPI()

@app.get("/api/orders")
def orders():
    token = "DYNAMIC_ACCESS_TOKEN"  # Replace with token from auth flow
    return {"orders": get_orders(token)}


✅ Rule for Agent:

Never hardcode tokens in production.

Always create a backend endpoint that the frontend can call.

⚙️ Step 4: Frontend Integration

The agent should fetch from /api/... routes, never directly from eBay.

React Example (OrdersDashboard.jsx):

import { useEffect, useState } from "react";

export default function OrdersDashboard() {
  const [orders, setOrders] = useState([]);

  useEffect(() => {
    fetch("/api/orders")
      .then(res => res.json())
      .then(data => setOrders(data.orders || []));
  }, []);

  return (
    <div className="p-4">
      <h1 className="text-xl font-bold">eBay Orders</h1>
      <table className="w-full border mt-4">
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th>Order ID</th>
            <th>Buyer</th>
            <th>Total</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          {orders.map(order => (
            <tr key={order.orderId}>
              <td>{order.orderId}</td>
              <td>{order.buyer.username}</td>
              <td>{order.pricingSummary.total.value} {order.pricingSummary.total.currency}</td>
            </tr>
          ))}
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
  );
}


✅ Rule for Agent:

Always fetch from /api/... backend routes.

Always render data in a dashboard-friendly format (tables, cards, charts).

📊 Supported eBay Data Modules

Orders → /sell/fulfillment/v1/order

Inventory → /sell/inventory/v1/inventory_item

Messages → /sell/communication/v1

Transactions → /finances/v1/transaction

Listings & Performance → /sell/analytics/v1

